<div class="steps">
  <!-- Step 0: Before You Start -->
  <div class="step">
    <div class="step__number">0</div>
    <h3 class="step__title">Before You Start</h3>
    <p class="step__description">
      Get these two free tools installed before the workshop. Both take a couple minutes.
    </p>
    <p class="step__description">
      <strong><a href="https://code.visualstudio.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">VS Code</a></strong> — A free code editor. You'll use this to see your project files and watch what Claude Code is building. Download, install, done.
    </p>
    <p class="step__description">
      <strong><a href="https://github.com/signup" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub account</a></strong> — Free. GitHub is where your code lives online. More importantly, it gives you version control: unlimited undo, branches to try ideas safely, and a backup of everything you build. Create an account if you don't have one.
    </p>
    <div class="step__note">
      The install script (Step 2) will install Claude Code for you automatically. If you already have it, it skips that step. You don't need to know Git commands either — Claude Code handles them for you.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 1 -->
  <div class="step">
    <div class="step__number">1</div>
    <h3 class="step__title">Clone the Repository</h3>
    <p class="step__description">
      Open Terminal (find it in Applications > Utilities) and run these commands:
    </p>
    <div class="step__code">
      <code>git clone https://github.com/erikaflowers/investiture.git
cd investiture</code>
    </div>
    <div class="step__note">
      If you see a popup asking to install "command line developer tools" — click Install. That's normal on a fresh Mac. It gives you Git. Once it finishes, run the commands above again.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 2 -->
  <div class="step">
    <div class="step__number">2</div>
    <h3 class="step__title">Run the Install Script</h3>
    <p class="step__description">
      This single command installs everything you need: Homebrew, Node.js, Claude Code, project dependencies, and creates your CLAUDE.md file.
    </p>
    <div class="step__code">
      <code>bash install.sh</code>
    </div>
    <div class="step__note">
      Works on all platforms without needing to set file permissions first.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 3 -->
  <div class="step">
    <div class="step__number">3</div>
    <h3 class="step__title">Start Your App</h3>
    <p class="step__description">
      Launch the development server. Your app will open automatically in your browser.
    </p>
    <div class="step__code">
      <code>npm start</code>
    </div>
    <div class="step__note">
      Opens at <a href="http://localhost:3000" target="_blank">http://localhost:3000</a>. When you edit files, the browser updates automatically.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 4 -->
  <div class="step">
    <div class="step__number">4</div>
    <h3 class="step__title">Open Claude Code</h3>
    <p class="step__description">
      The install script already installed Claude Code for you. Launch it in your project folder — it reads the CLAUDE.md file automatically and understands your project structure.
    </p>
    <div class="step__code">
      <code>claude</code>
    </div>
    <div class="step__note">
      Make sure you're still in the investiture directory when you launch Claude Code. The first time you run it, you'll need to log in with your Anthropic account. Go to <a href="https://console.anthropic.com/" target="_blank">console.anthropic.com</a> to create one if you haven't already.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 5 -->
  <div class="step">
    <div class="step__number">5</div>
    <h3 class="step__title">Start Building</h3>
    <p class="step__description">
      Try one of these prompts in Claude Code. Your app updates in real time as Claude makes changes.
    </p>
    <div class="step__code">
      <code>"Change the app title and tagline using content/en.json"

"Add a dark mode toggle using the design tokens"

"Add a todo list that uses content strings, design tokens, and core logic"

"Fetch data from a public API and display it in cards"</code>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

